channel.title: Terrorize other computers on your home network!
channel.description:
[b]This will not work on XP Home. If someone know a way to use the telnet service on XP Home (even if means downloading an emulator or something), PLEASE tell me. I really need it.[/b]
First, go the the computer on your home network (brother/sister/parents computer etc.), and when they are not looking, go to Control Panel > Administrative Tools > Services, start Telnet, and set its startup type to automatic ([b]Be sure you enable telnet on your own computer as well![/b]). Then on the same computer, go to Start > Run, type "control userpasswords2", highlight the administrator password, and click the "Reset Password" button. Be sure you set a password that you remember, don't leave it blank. Most home users don't bother to set the administrator password, so this should work. Now go to Start > Run and type "cmd". In command prompt, type "ipconfig". To the left of the IP Address row, there should be an IP address, write it down.
Ok, now you have the victims pc set up and have the IP address. Now, go to your computer, go to Start > Run, type "cmd" and press enter. Now in command prompt, type "telnet". Type "o %VictimsIp%". For example, I might type "o 192.168.0.1". Now it should ask you a yes or no question (forgot what it is), just enter "y". Now it should say "login: ". Just enter "Administrator". Then it should say "password:". Obviously, enter the password you set for Administrator on the victims computer. Note that as you type, the password field will appear blank, but it is still recording what you type.
So, now you are in. You can type commands as if you are running command prompt on their own computer. So, you could type "taskkill \F \IM firefox.exe", "taskkill \F \IM explorer.exe", and such. You could even just shut it down with "shutdown -s". Or, if you want to be a jerk, type "format c: /fs:ntfs". Basically, anything that can be done in command prompt if you were right there in the chair typing on their computer, can be done using your computer remotely.
Have fun, I use it a lot, freaks my parents out because they don't know what's going on (they know nothing about computers).

item.dc:creator: @vbcoderx vbcoderx
item.description:
@vbcoderx wrote:

u don’t have to have the telnet service to connect out of ur comp. The comp u connect to just has to have it. MS might have removed it from home edition to make it less prone to attacks like this. Since who would want to connect to a home edition machine for good purposes anyway? XP Pro has it because it was designed to be used by busienesses, thats also why windows xp pro comes with IIS. if u want to connect to a comp on ur network that HAS telnet service running u would need to hit windows key + r then type cmd then type ipconfig. That should list the Ip’s of the computers on your network. Then hit windows key + r and type telnet then when telnet opens type o Ipaddress. then it will ask you stuff about logging in like i think Zach1188 said. OR you could just download a nice vb6 trojan that hasn’t been mass released from a hacking website. There are thousands of them out there. but i sudgest to only download sources or u may get hacked by someone! also there has be no Microsoft Official release of SP3. If you have SP3 then it is made by someone. Probably by best buy maybe. U can slipstream all of microsoft’s updates into an xp installation cd. OR u can use a program called nlite that does it for you, but u can also add programs like antivirus and firewall and the sweet WMP11.
